Just now

--

Most Next.js routing tutorials you’ll find were written for the Pages Router, and a lot of the code in them no longer compiles. The classic tell is a <Link> with an <a> tag nested inside it. That pattern was deprecated in Next.js 13 and it's gone now. If you copy it into a fresh project you'll get an error, not a link.
So here’s the same “build a small multi-page site” walkthrough, but written against the App Router the way Next.js 16 actually wants it. I built and ran every file below on Next.js 16.2.10 with React 19 before writing this.
Why multiple real pages still matter
Single-page apps get all the attention, but plenty of sites are better off as distinct pages with their own URLs: marketing sites, docs, blogs, anything where each page needs to be indexable and shareable on its own. The App Router gives you that with server components by default, so each route ships less client JavaScript unless you ask for more.
Start a project
You need Node installed, then:
npx create-next-app@latest my-nextjs-appTake the App Router when it asks (that’s the default now). Then:
cd my-nextjs-app
npm run devPages are folders now, not files
The old Pages Router mapped pages/about.tsx to /about. The App Router maps a folder with a page.tsx inside it. So /about is app/about/page.tsx. The root page is app/page.tsx.
Here’s a home page. Note it’s a plain server component — no "use client", no hooks, nothing shipped to the browser:
import NavBar from '@/components/NavBar';export default function HomePage() {
return (
<div>
<NavBar />
<h1>Welcome to the Home Page</h1>
<p>This is the main landing page of the website.</p>
</div>
);
}And the about page at app/about/page.tsx:
import NavBar from '@/components/NavBar';export default function AboutPage() {
return (
<div>
<NavBar />
<h1>About Us</h1>
<p>This page gives information about the company.</p>
</div>
);
}Those are live at / and /about with no route config anywhere. The folder structure is the config.
Navigation: the part that breaks in old tutorials
This is where copied code goes wrong. In current Next.js, <Link> renders the anchor tag for you. You put the text or children directly inside it — no wrapper <a>:
import Link from 'next/link';export default function NavBar() {
return (
<nav>
<ul>
<li><Link href="/">Home</Link></li>
<li><Link href="/about">About</Link></li>
</ul>
</nav>
);
}If you’re moving an old codebase over, there’s a new-link codemod that strips the nested <a> tags for you. Worth running rather than doing it by hand across a big app.
Dynamic routes
A blog needs one template that handles /blog/1, /blog/hello-world, and everything else. You get that with a bracketed folder name: app/blog/[id]/page.tsx. The [id] becomes a param.
The catch that trips people up on Next.js 15 and 16: params is a Promise. You await it. This changed from the older synchronous shape, so old examples that read params.id directly will not work.
export default async function BlogPost({
params,
}: {
params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
}) {
const { id } = await params; return (
<div>
<h1>Blog Post {id}</h1>
<p>This is the content of the blog post with id {id}.</p>
</div>
);
}Hit /blog/1 or /blog/some-title and id is whatever you put in the URL. Because this is a server component, you'd typically await getPost(id) right here and render real data — no client-side fetch, no loading spinner for the initial render.
The one thing to remember
When you follow a Next.js routing tutorial, check its date and check for a nested <a> inside <Link>. If it has one, it predates the App Router and half its patterns are stale. The three that matter today: pages are folders with a page.tsx, <Link> needs no inner anchor, and params is a Promise you await. Everything above built clean on Next.js 16.2.10 — the routes for /, /about, and /blog/[id] all came out of next build without a single change.
